We can rewrite the equations using the properties of logarithms:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \log _{10}\left(x^{3}\right)+\log _{10}\left(y^{2}\right)=11 \\
& \log _{10}\left(x^{2}\right)-\log _{10}\left(y^{3}\right)=3
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the property $\log_{a}(b^{c}) = c\log_{a}(b)$, we can rewrite the equations as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 3\log_{10}(x) + 2\log_{10}(y) = 11 \\
& 2\log_{10}(x) - 3\log_{10}(y) = 3
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, we can add the two equations together to eliminate $\log_{10}(y)$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& (3\log_{10}(x) + 2\log_{10}(y)) + (2\log_{10}(x) - 3\log_{10}(y)) = 11 + 3 \\
& 5\log_{10}(x) = 14 \\
& \log_{10}(x) = \frac{14}{5}
\end{aligned}
$$

Taking the logarithm base 10 of both sides, we get:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \log_{10}(x) = \frac{14}{5} \\
& x = 10^{\frac{14}{5}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the solution to the system of equations is $x = \boxed{10^{\frac{14}{5}}}$.
The answer is: 10^{\frac{14}{5}}

